    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:24b0a7db-aad3-4314-9b81-0546a18e6eb8",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 71-year-old woman who appears older than her stated age, with a lean frame and a tired, guarded posture that reflects months of declining stamina. She often pauses to catch her breath after short walks and has a frequent dry-to-productive cough that occasionally interrupts conversation. Her face shows mild temporal wasting and a drawn expression, but she remains attentive, polite, and determined to stay engaged in her care. She dresses neatly and usually carries a small shoulder bag stocked with tissues, cough drops, and a notebook where she tracks appointments and symptoms.\n\nShe lives alone in a small suburban apartment since being widowed several years ago, though her adult daughter visits frequently and helps with groceries, transportation, and medication organization. Before retirement, {patientName} worked for decades as a school librarian and still enjoys reading historical fiction, tending a few balcony plants, and speaking with former colleagues by phone. She used to be active in a neighborhood walking group but now limits activity because of exertional dyspnea, chest discomfort, and fatigue. Her appetite has diminished, and she has unintentionally lost weight over recent months.\n\nHer symptoms began insidiously with a persistent cough, then progressive shortness of breath, reduced exercise tolerance, intermittent right-sided chest pain, and increasing fatigue. More recently she has noticed occasional streaks of blood in the sputum and a dull ache in the upper back. She feels anxious about the diagnosis but is pragmatic and asks direct questions about treatment goals, side effects, and prognosis. She has a long smoking history and describes feeling guilty about it, though she quit after the diagnostic workup began.\n\nSocially, {patientName} is close to her daughter, a younger sister, and two old friends from work who check in regularly. She values independence and is frustrated by needing help, yet she remains motivated to attend oncology visits and continue treatment. Her daily routine now revolves around conserving energy, resting between tasks, and planning outings around symptom burden. Despite the seriousness of illness, she still finds comfort in books, music from her youth, and time with family."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:12918d2f-b54c-47e9-aad4-9d241a7963d9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a significant tobacco exposure history of approximately 45 pack-years and stopped smoking only recently after evaluation for persistent respiratory symptoms. Her past medical history includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, hypertension, and hyperlipidemia. Over the last 6 months, she has had progressive cough, exertional dyspnea, anorexia, and an unintentional 8-kg weight loss. She was hospitalized once in the past year for post-obstructive pneumonia requiring intravenous antibiotics and supplemental oxygen.\n\nShe is generally adherent to medical care but has become more dependent on family support because of declining endurance. She drinks alcohol rarely and denies illicit drug use. Functional status has worsened from fully independent community ambulation to needing frequent rest breaks with housework and shopping. Recent oncology evaluation identified a right upper lobe lung mass, and bronchoscopy with biopsy confirmed malignancy. She is now undergoing systemic therapy with palliative intent while also receiving symptom-directed treatment for pain, cough, and treatment-related nausea."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}